[1]
Date: 14 Apr 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Boston Globe 14 Apr 2004 [edited]
<http://www.boston.com/news/world/articles/2004/04/14/botswana_polio_case_shocks_officials/>


Botswana polio case shocks officials: finding is setback for eradication
effort
-----------------------------------------------
The effort to eradicate polio worldwide by year's end 2004 received a major
jolt yesterday Tue 13 Apr 2004 as health investigators confirmed a new case
in Botswana that they [linked] to northern Nigeria 3000 miles away. The new
case served as a reminder that the threat of polio's spread is ever-present
and spurred Botswana officials to begin planning a nation-wide immunization
program.

"This shows unless the virus is eradicated everywhere, no one is protected
anywhere," Jean-Marie Okwo-Bele, senior adviser for immunization activities
at UNICEF in New York, said in a telephone interview. "As long as we have
a couple of pockets of transmission, we are not safe at all."

The infection of a 7-year-old boy in northeastern Botswana -- the 1st case
in southern Africa since 1997 -- shocked international and local health
officials. Botswana officials said last night -- Tue 13 Apr -- that, in
response, they plan to conduct 2 rounds of house-to-house immunizations
nationwide starting in May 2004 involving all children under the age of 5.
They hope to reach 250 000 children, at a cost close to USD 1 million.

Health officials said they still hope this setback will not block the goal
of eradication by the end of 2004. But they added that much depends on
halting the spread soon in Nigeria, where anti-American sentiment has
fueled suspicion of the vaccine. If they are successful, polio will be only
the 2nd disease affecting humans that has been eradicated, following smallpox.

"It's really still way too premature to [give up on] the 2004 goal, but if we
don't get 2 [immunization] rounds in the spring [of 2004] in northern
Nigeria, it will make it really, really tough," said Bruce Aylward, the World
Health Organization's polio eradication coordinator.

Polio cases around the world have decreased by 99 percent since 1988, when
an estimated 350 000 people were infected. In 2003, 784 cases were
reported, a major drop from 1918 cases in 2002, but still higher than the
figures for 2000 and 2001. In 2003, Nigeria accounted for 45 percent of the
world's cases. In 2004, as of 7 Apr, Nigeria has 48 of the world's 72
reported infections, or 2/3.

Several Muslim and secular leaders in sections of northern Nigeria have
effectively shut down efforts to vaccinate children for polio for nearly a
year because of rumors that the vaccine was tainted in an American plot to
sterilize Muslim children. Some Muslim leaders also have said that even if
the vaccine is safe, they will boycott the immunizations simply because the
United States is a major funder in polio eradication; they say it is their
way of protesting US wars in the predominantly Muslim countries of
Afghanistan and Iraq.

In the face of such opposition, Nigerian and international leaders have
gone to great lengths to convince skeptics the vaccine is safe. A 23-member
panel traveled this year to laboratories in Indonesia, South Africa, and
India, where samples of the vaccine were tested. The committee, which
included 2 officials from the northern Nigerian state of Kano, concluded in
mid-Mar 2004 that the vaccines were safe, but Kano leaders have yet to
comment.

The next immunization in Nigeria is planned for late April 2004. In March
2004, Kano was the only state not to participate.

In contrast to Nigeria, the efforts to eradicate polio have proceeded well
in recent months in India, Pakistan, Afghanistan, Egypt, and Niger -- the
other 5 countries where the virus is endemic. In India and Pakistan
particularly, the immunization campaigns have gone better than expected.

"It's pretty exciting progress around the rest of the world," Aylward
said. "Maybe the Botswana case will heighten the need for international
cooperation in attacking the problem in Nigeria."

At first, health officials were not sure whether to believe the lab results
of the Botswana polio case. They hashed out one theory that it could have
come from a contaminated sample in a South African lab which tests samples
from around Africa.

They ordered more tests. Scientists tested the genetic sequencing of the
virus and determined it was a better than 99 percent match with the virus
type found in northern Nigeria. They plan to officially announce the
results today, Wed 14 Apr.

"It is definitely from northern Nigeria," said Deo Nshimirimana, WHO's
regional adviser in Africa for vaccine preventable diseases, in a telephone
interview from Harare, Zimbabwe. "We tested it and re-tested it. The only
way we know it is linked to Nigeria is that the lab shows the virus is
related to the one there."

But no one knows how the 7-year-old boy became infected. The boy,
Nshimirimana said, showed weakness in his limbs, but later recovered and
now is apparently suffering no ill-effects. Only about 10 percent of such
cases do not involve a degree of paralysis.

In Botswana, local investigators canvassed his neighborhood and visited
others who came in contact with him. But officials in Gabarone, the
Botswana capital, said they have found no one who has been to Nigeria
recently or who has been in contact with someone who has traveled there.
The poliomyelitis virus, which affects mainly children and often cripples
their legs and arms, is most often transmitted by drinking water
contaminated by infected feces or by contaminated hands.

"We have not, as a country, confirmed this is an imported case," said Dr.
Patson Mazonde, Botswana's director of health services. "We have teams in
the field. Until their work is done, we will not have a conclusion."

[Byline: John Donnelly]

